        <title type="html"><![CDATA[Personalizing Docusaurus]]></title>
        <id>setup-styling-docusaurus</id>
        <link href="https://www.laurentlao.com/blog/setup-styling-docusaurus"/>
        <updated>2022-03-12T00:00:00.000Z</updated>
        <summary type="html"><![CDATA[Phew, just finished the first draft of the personalization of my website. I chose the Nord palette since my development environment also uses that colour palette. This means that having my documentation website open right next to my IDE results in a single design language and is very aesthetically pleasing.]]></summary>
        <content type="html"><![CDATA[<p>Phew, just finished the first draft of the personalization of my website. I chose the <a href="https://www.nordtheme.com/docs/colors-and-palettes" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Nord palette</a> since my development environment also uses that colour palette. This means that having my documentation website open right next to my IDE results in a single design language and is very aesthetically pleasing.</p><p>Since I started with the <code>classic</code> template from Docusaurus, a lot of the theming of my website was already done, but it followed Docusaurus's colour palette. After some inspection with the browser and reading this <a href="https://theochu.com/docusaurus/styling/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">blog</a>, I started to understand how the CSS is handled in Docusaurus.</p><p>I also experimented with the <a href="https://www.npmjs.com/package/typewriter-effect" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">typewriter-effect</a> library and imported it as a React component to act as my main header page (and add a little flair).</p><p>Finally, I added GitHub Actions to automatically deploy my website when <code>main</code> is updated, which makes adding new content extremely easy. I can boot up my developer environment, or straight up use Github's editor, and my website will be updated.</p><p>Very nice!</p>]]></content>
